t- reads active session metadata from `.git/entire-sessions/<session-id>.json` when needed\n33\t- extracts durable lessons such as repo conventions, validation commands, user corrections, required inputs, and behaviors to avoid\n34\t- drafts a focused `SKILL.md` instead of recapping the whole session\n35\t- asks before writing, installing, or overwriting a skill\n36\t\n37\t### `explain`\n38\t\n39\tTraces source code back to the original conversation where it was created. Use `/explain` with a function, file, or line of code to understand _why_ it exists.\n40\t\n41\tCurrent behavior:\n42\t\n43\t- identifies the commit that introduced the code via git blame/log\n44\t- reads the session transcript via `entire explain --no-pager --commit <sha>`\n45\t- works with functions, files, and individual line changes\n46\t- reports clearly when code is untracked, uncommitted, or created outside an Entire session\n47\t\n48\t### `what-happened`\n49\t\n50\tExplains what happened to a specific code block by tracing the latest change for a file line,\n51\trange, or pasted snippet through git blame and Entire checkpoints.\n52\t\n53\tCurrent behavior:\n54\t\n55\t- resolves file lines, ranges, or pasted snippets to exact line numbers\n56\t- asks for a concrete file line, range, or snippet before running provenance commands\n57\t- deduplicates commit and checkpoint lookups before running expensive transcript commands\n58\t- asks before expanding broad ranges with many unique commits\n59\t- summarizes `entire explain` output without dumping raw transcripts by default; raw transcript expansion is opt-in\n60\t- falls back to clearly labeled current-code analysis when checkpoint-backed context is unavailable\n61\t\n62\tExamples:\n63\t\n64\t- \"tell me why this code is like that\"\n65\t- \"why does this code look like this?\"\n66\t- \"what happened here: `src/auth.ts:42-57`\"\n67\t- \"what happened at `src/auth.ts:42`\"\n68\t- \"what happened to this block?\" plus a pasted snippet\n69\t\n70\t#