<checkpoint-id> --full --no-pager\n74\t```\n75\t\n76\tIf `--full` fails for a checkpoint, fall back to:\n77\t\n78\t```bash\n79\tentire explain --checkpoint <checkpoint-id> --raw-transcript --no-pager\n80\t```\n81\t\n82\t7. Build the playbook in this order:\n83\t\n84\t```text\n85\tEntire Recall:\n86\t\n87\t## Closest precedent\n88\t<one-line summary> — checkpoint <id>, <date>, <author>\n89\t\n90\t## What worked\n91\t- <distilled approach point>\n92\t- <distilled approach point>\n93\t- <distilled approach point>\n94\t\n95\t## Gotchas\n96\t- <error or dead end and how it was resolved>\n97\t- <surprising constraint>\n98\t\n99\t## Files touched\n100\t- <path> (<n> mentions)\n101\t- <path> (<n> mentions)\n102\t\n103\t## Suggested approach for your task\n104\t<2-4 sentences applying the precedent to the new task, naming the specific files or steps to start with>\n105\t\n106\t## Other relevant precedents\n107\t- checkpoint <id> — <one-line summary>\n108\t- checkpoint <id> — <one-line summary>\n109\t```\n110\t\n111\t- Anchor every claim to a checkpoint ID, file path, or commit SHA. Do not paraphrase without an anchor.\n112\t- Keep \"What worked\" and \"Gotchas\" tight (3-5 bullets each). If the transcript does not surface a real gotcha, omit the section rather than padding it.\n113\t- \"Suggested approach for your task\" should be concrete enough to start working from — name the file or function or command to begin with.\n114\t\n115\t## Failure Modes\n116\t\n117\t- If the first two searches return zero useful hits, broaden in this order and report each attempt:\n118\t  1. Simplify the query to its single strongest noun\n119\t  2. Drop the `--date` filter\n120\t  3. Remove any `--branch` or `--repo` constraints\n121\t- If still empty after broadening, say clearly: `No prior sessions matched. Tried: <queries and filters>.` Do not invent a precedent.\n122\t- If a top hit's transcript cannot be read via `--full` or `--raw-transcript`, drop it from the playbook and use the next-best hit. Note the dropped checkpoint ID at the end of the playbook so the user can investigate manually.\n123\t"}]},"uuid":"3fcfb6e5-bd30-4e4c-9f49-e59d0c3a18ca","timestamp":"2026-05-01T16:30:29.091Z","toolUseResult":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/alisha/.marvin/worktrees/skills/search-skills/skills/recall/SKILL.md","content":"---\nname: recall\ndescription: \"Use when the user describes a task and wants to know whether something similar has been done before, then turn the closest prior session into a task playbook. Triggers on phrases like \\\"have we done this before\\\", \\\"recall how we did X\\\", \\\"find similar work\\\", \\\"any precedent for\\\", \\\"has anyone solved\\\", \\\"is there a template for\\\", and \\\"how did we do this last time\\\"\"\n---\n\n# Entire Recall\n\nUse `entire search` and `entire explain` to recall the closest prior session for a task and turn it into a playbook the user can act on. This is task-shaped, not list-shaped: the goal is \"here's how to do your task\" rather than \"here are some checkpoints.\"\n\n## Response Format\n\nBegin the first response to this skill invocation with the line:\n\n`Entire Recall:`\n\nfollowed by a blank line, then the content.\n\n- Apply the header to the **first response of the invocation only.** Do not re-print it on follow-up turns within the same invocation.\n- Do **not** include the header on error or early-exit responses (missing CLI, missing auth, not inside a git repo, no matches after documented broadening).\n\n## When to Use\n\n- The user is about to start a task and wants to see how similar work was done before\n- The user says things like \"have we done this before?\", \"recall how we did X\", \"find similar work\", \"has anyone solved X?\", \"how did we do this last time?\"\n- You want a precedent transformed into a playbook, not a raw list of checkpoints\n\nIf the user just wants a search result list, switch to the `search` skill instead.\n\n## Guardrails\n\n- Treat repositor